    <div class="page-title">
      <h3 class="h1"><a href="http://localhost:4000/2016-06-02/democratizing-design-with-the-design-studio-method/">Democratizing design with the Design Studio method</a></h3>
    </div>
    
    <p>It takes a village to make a great digital product. Here‚Äôs how we do it at <a href="http://arcweb.co">Arcweb Technologies</a>.</p>

<!-- more -->

<p class="notice-info">This post is an adaptation of <a href="/speaking/2015-11-18/tech2gether/">the talk I gave at Tech2Gether</a> in November of 2015. You can read what Technical.ly said about it <a href="http://technical.ly/delaware/2015/11/20/heres-firms-consider-democratizing-design-process/">here.</a></p>

<p>You‚Äôve all heard the phrase ‚Äú<a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/stevedenning/2014/04/11/why-software-is-eating-the-world/#240ccbb33b24">Software is eating the world,</a>‚ÄĚ right? I find that a weird way to look at things, but it‚Äôs still an interesting point. Everywhere you look, there‚Äôs a new previously dumb device adding software to stay competitive. There‚Äôs even a <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Quirky-Minder-Wink-Enabled-Smart/dp/B00GN92KQ4">connected egg tray</a> that sits in your fridge now and tells your smartphone when your eggs might go bad. What a time to be alive, right?</p>

<p>But the one thing you‚Äôll notice, is that if software is in fact eating the world, <em>design is leading the way.</em></p>

<p>You can‚Äôt pick up a <a href="https://hbr.org/archive-toc/BR1509">business</a> <a href="http://www.fastcodesign.com">mag</a> these days without finding a <a href="https://hbr.org/2015/09/design-thinking-comes-of-age">feature article</a> on design. The <a href="http://apple.com">richest company in the world right now</a> got there largely because of design. And, I have personally dealt with several large engineering-driven product companies that are working to become more design-driven, because that‚Äôs where the market is headed. Huge, well-funded companies are realizing that without design, they‚Äôre dead.</p>

<p>Well, I‚Äôm a designer by trade, and to me, and all the other designers in the room, I bet that sounds great, right? Right?</p>

<p>Not so fast.</p>

<h3 id="i-want-to-let-you-all-in-on-a-little-secret">I want to let you all in on a little secret</h3>

<p>Don‚Äôt tell anyone I told you this, ok? Here it is:</p>
<blockquote>
  <p>Design is too important to be left to designers.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Huh?</p>

<h3 id="design-is-too-important-to-be-left-to-designers">Design is too important to be left to designers</h3>

<p>Ok, now I have the attention of all the designers in the room, because they‚Äôre mad. And rightfully so, because it sounds like I just said your job is too much for you. Hold up. What does that mean?</p>

<h3 id="well-actually">Well, actually‚Ä¶</h3>

<p>Today‚Äôs digital products are just so complex. Really, to land with any sort of traction in the marketplace, you probably have to launch on iOS, on Android, and on the web, for starters. Which means there‚Äôs a cloud component. You have to know what‚Äôs out there in the market. You need to have someone calling the shots from a product perspective. There‚Äôs a lot that goes into what we call user experience design these days‚Ä¶ and that‚Äôs <em>before</em> we even get to the actual users!</p>

<p>So, really, we‚Äôre actually talking about something that‚Äôs a little different than what those who attended art school would call ‚Äúdesign.‚ÄĚ</p>

<p>We, as user experience designers, have to adjust the way we think about out roles. Sure, there‚Äôs a lot of ‚Äúdesigning‚ÄĚ that still has to happen. But today‚Äôs UX or product designer spends a lot less time pixel pushing and more time as the steward of the design process.</p>

<h2 id="ux-design-as-stewardship">UX design as stewardship</h2>

<p>A UX designer‚Äôs role, today and going forward, whether you know it or not, is to create the best possible experience for your users. Full stop. Doesn‚Äôt matter where it comes from. Doesn‚Äôt matter how you get there, really. You‚Äôre not a ninja or rockstar, who comes down from on high and blesses the masses with your talents. You‚Äôre a steward, and you‚Äôre a part of a team.</p>

<p>So, how do you pivot from being a pixel pusher to a design steward? Here‚Äôs how we do it at Arcweb Technologies.</p>

<h2 id="the-arcweb-technologies-design-studio">The Arcweb Technologies Design Studio</h2>

<p>We do Design Studio. Design Studio isn‚Äôt a place; it‚Äôs a methodology. It‚Äôs not a proprietary thing, or even a new idea. You can start doing this tomorrow if you like. Hey, we‚Äôll be happy to <a href="http://arcweb.co/contact">conduct a workshop</a> with your company or startup to show you how (<em>hint hint</em>). So what is it?</p>

<p>Design Studio is a methodology we use to create digital products people love. There are three core ideas behind it:</p>

<ol>
  <li>It‚Äôs <strong>collaborative.</strong> We get as many people as possible involved as early as possible.</li>
  <li>It‚Äôs <strong>cross-disciplinary.</strong> Design Studio participants are not just designers. I know, right? But that‚Äôs the point. To create truly great digital products, we need <strong>everyone‚Äôs</strong> input. That means product managers, engineers, architects, QA folks, product owners, marketing, whoever. Everyone‚Äôs got a valid opinion to bring, and we want to collect them all.</li>
  <li>It‚Äôs <strong>participatory.</strong> We don‚Äôt only talk about design. We <strong>do</strong> design in design studio. And how do we do that?</li>
</ol>

<h3 id="sketching">Sketching</h3>

<p>We sketch. <em>Relentlessly.</em> Sketches are the coin of the realm in design studio. Without a sketch, an idea is just words. It‚Äôs not concrete. It‚Äôs ephemeral. It‚Äôs much harder to react to. I can‚Äôt circle the part of your voice that isn‚Äôt working, or highlight the part that is, right? Plus, sketching isn‚Äôt Photoshop. It isn‚Äôt Sublime Text. It isn‚Äôt Powerpoint. No one‚Äôs in their comfort zone, using their preferred tool. We‚Äôre all on equal footing.</p>

<p>Before we go much further, I can hear what some of you are thinking‚Ä¶</p>

<h3 id="but-i-cant-draw">‚ÄúBut I can‚Äôt draw!‚ÄĚ</h3>

<p>I want to let you in on another little secret: <em>I can‚Äôt draw, either.</em> Seriously. It‚Äôs really bad. I didn‚Äôt go to art school. But I‚Äôll tell you what I sure as hell can do: I can sketch well enough to communicate a design idea, pitch it to someone and get their buy-in. That‚Äôs all we‚Äôre trying to do here. Sketching isn‚Äôt drawing. There‚Äôs no aesthetic goal for sketching.</p>

<p>Let me repeat that: <strong>Sketching isn‚Äôt drawing.</strong> Here, look:</p>

<p><img src="/assets/images/articles/like-this.jpg" alt="Like this:" /></p>

<p>These are the kinds of sketches we‚Äôre looking for. Juuuuuuust enough detail to convey your idea. That‚Äôs a login page, there‚Äôs kind of a landing page, and that‚Äôs a modal overlay. That took me maybe 20 seconds. That‚Äôs all you need.</p>

<p>This is what we mean when we say Design Studio is <em>participatory.</em>  Everyone in the room picks up a sharpie and sketches. If you‚Äôre not sketching, you‚Äôre not in the room. We‚Äôre all in this together, people. Besides, if you‚Äôve been invited to our design studio, it‚Äôs not necessarily because I like you or want to hang out or whatever, it‚Äôs because I need your ideas. So <strong>everyone</strong> participates. This is non-negotiable.</p>

<h2 id="how-to-design-studio">How to Design Studio</h2>

<p>So, how do you ‚Äúdo‚ÄĚ design studio? It‚Äôs a four step process.</p>

<h3 id="define">Define</h3>

<p>Defining the problem you hope your Design Studio will solve is the first, often overlooked and maybe most important step. Of course, it‚Äôs good to know what you‚Äôre trying to accomplish with a given design, but it‚Äôs great to know this cold up-front, because by defining the problem up front, you have a framework for evaluating a design‚Äôs effectiveness later, so you don‚Äôt have to resort to ‚ÄúI like it, just because.‚ÄĚ (More on feedback in a minute.) It‚Äôs also helpful to have your personas in place. These are mini-dossiers about your users, and what they‚Äôre trying to accomplish by using your software.</p>

<h3 id="create">Create</h3>

<p>Now, we create. But we do this in a very prescribed, constrained manner. We take grid paper and Sharpies and everyone in the room sketches 6-8 ways to solve the problem for the given persona in 5 minutes.</p>

<p>That‚Äôs a lot to unpack, and there‚Äôs a reason for each of these constraints.</p>

<p><strong>Why graph paper?</strong> Because there‚Äôs enough uncertainty and uncomfortableness around this process, that we want to give people some framework to feel comfortable it. Most software is made of straight lines, and the graph paper helps us remember this.</p>

<p><strong>Why Sharpies?</strong> Sharpies are fat and indelible. You can‚Äôt spend too much time on detail with a sharpie, and you can‚Äôt go back and erase.</p>

<p><strong>Why 6-8 sketches?</strong> Because that‚Äôs a lot, and we want to keep your hand moving, not thinking. We want you to silence your internal critic and help you focus on getting the idea on paper.</p>

<p><strong>Why 5 minutes?</strong> Because you can accomplish a lot more than you think in 5 minutes.</p>

<h3 id="pitch">Pitch</h3>

<p>So once we‚Äôre done the five minute sketch session, we pitch our sketches to each other. <strong>Pitching is where the magic happens.</strong> Everyone grabs some painters tape and tapes their sketches up onto the wall. Then, you get a minute to pitch. What were you hoping to accomplish with your sketches? Why did you go this route? What assumptions did you make?</p>

<h3 id="critique">Critique</h3>

<p>Once everyone has pitched, we enter the critiquing stage of design studio. This is where the definition of the problem I discussed earlier become so important. That gives you an agreed-upon framework for discussing ideas. It allows you to say ‚ÄúThis works for our target user because‚Ä¶ ‚Äú rather than ‚ÄúI like this.‚ÄĚ Such a simple turn of a phrase, but so powerful. Once we take our feelings out of the equation, it becomes so much easier to give and receive honest, helpful feedback.</p>

<p>After the pitch and critique, everyone gets  three glue dots to tag the sketches they think are most effectively solving the problem. They can put all three on one sketch if they really love it. They can tag their own. The only rule is, three dots per person. The sketch with the most dots gives the group direction on where to go next.</p>

<h3 id="lather-rinse-repeat">Lather, rinse, repeat</h3>

<p>So, once you‚Äôve gone through one iteration, you can pick a new feature, define it, sketch it, pitch it, and critique it. Or, you can pick a direction that your team seemed to favor in the first round and dive deeper into it. It‚Äôs up to you and your team.</p>

<h2 id="why-design-studio">Why Design Studio?</h2>

<p>So, now that we‚Äôve discussed what Design Studio is and isn‚Äôt, why do we like it so much?</p>

<h3 id="requirements">Requirements</h3>

<p>It‚Äôs great for requirements gathering: in the Define stage, we can learn everyone‚Äôs opinions on what ‚Äúneeds‚ÄĚ to be in the product for a 1.0 version.</p>

<h3 id="prioritization">Prioritization</h3>

<p>By seeing where everyone leans in the sketching phase, we can get a real sense of where things fall on the must have/nice to have/someday spectrum.</p>

<h3 id="idea-generation">Idea generation</h3>

<p>There is no better way to generate lots of different ideas than a Design Studio. <em>None.</em> This makes Design Studio great for any stage in the product development lifecycle: when you‚Äôre starting out on a project, or even when you‚Äôre stuck on a particular feature, or any time in between.</p>

<h3 id="consensus-building">Consensus Building</h3>

<p>One of my favorite outcomes of a good design studio is consensus building. Because you have all the stakeholders in the room, and everyone was a part of the ideation and pitching and critiquing, people feel more involved. They feel like they‚Äôve been <em>heard.</em> Plus, you walk out of a design studio with pre-vetted ideas. Everyone participated in coming up with them. They belong to the group. You don‚Äôt have designers saying ‚ÄúI wish I had been invited to an earlier meeting‚ÄĚ or engineers saying ‚ÄúThere‚Äôs no way we can do that‚ÄĚ or product owners saying ‚ÄúWhy am I seeing this for the first time?‚ÄĚ</p>

<h3 id="speed">Speed</h3>
<p>I‚Äôve seen and anecdotally heard about teams that implement some kind of Design Studio shaving weeks, even months off of a project‚Äôs timeline. It eliminates the back-and-forth nature of a lot of product engagements.</p>

<h3 id="empathy">Empathy</h3>

<p>But here‚Äôs the real kicker. After going through a design studio with a team, <em>you can‚Äôt help but respect and empathize with your team more.</em></p>

<p>A Design Studio can honestly be a bit of a stressful situation. No one‚Äôs totally comfortable, and everyone‚Äôs on the line to pitch and defend their ideas. That builds a team sometimes. Hearing people explain their ideas and defend them in a controlled environment helps you gain insight into them. Your engineers start to understand that designers don‚Äôt just suggest things to make their lives difficult. Designers understand that engineers don‚Äôt say no ‚Äújust because.‚ÄĚ</p>

<p>This benefit carries through long after the Design Studio session is complete. And, while we‚Äôve seen better products come out of our sessions, <strong>the real deliverable of a good Design Studio is better teams.</strong></p>

<h2 id="your-homework">Your homework</h2>

<p>I have a homework assignment for you. Take your next feature and run it through a Design Studio. Doesn‚Äôt matter how small. You can do it in as little as 90 minutes if that‚Äôs all you have, but any time you spend will be well worth it. And if you‚Äôd like me to come discuss how to do this in more detail, <a href="http://arcweb.co/contact">here‚Äôs how to get in touch.</a></p>

<p>Thank you all so much, and happy sketching!</p>

    
