    <div class="page-title">
      <h3 class="h1"><a href="http://localhost:4000/2012-12-06/the-thing-about-git/">The Thing About Git</a></h3>
    </div>
    
    <p>All it takes is about 300 lines of accidentally-deleted CSS before you say, ‚ÄúYou know what? Maybe it‚Äôs time to get serious about version control.‚ÄĚ Which means it‚Äôs time for the scary, scary command line. Terrifying for someone who hasn‚Äôt been living in it for a while.</p>

<p>But wait! A cursory Google search reveals that there are bunch of native Mac apps for Git! With beautiful GUIs! Clickable buttons! None of that scary <code class="highlighter-rouge">$</code> nonsense!</p>

<p>It seems like a lifeline, a way in. An easier way to learn this monstrosity that is Git. I‚Äôll dive into all that command line stuff later.</p>

<p>Except it doesn‚Äôt work that way.</p>

<p>Let‚Äôs take <a href="http://www.git-tower.com/">Tower</a>, for instance. My goodness, is this a beautiful app. Just look at it!</p>

<p><img src="/assets/images/articles/pull-requests.png" alt="" /></p>

<p>Just the type of polish you‚Äôd expect from a best-in-class Mac app.</p>

<p>But‚Ä¶ wait. What do those buttons mean? What are <code class="highlighter-rouge">Push</code> and <code class="highlighter-rouge">Pull</code>? What‚Äôs <code class="highlighter-rouge">Commit</code> mean? I have commitment issues‚Ä¶ not gonna mess with that thing. And what are all those letters in colored boxes?</p>

<p>No matter how beautiful the app, you have to understand Git conceptually, or else it‚Äôs useless. You‚Äôre just pushing buttons.</p>

<p>Terminal-phobes: I know it‚Äôs scary, but you‚Äôre going to have to get your hands dirty sooner or later. You can‚Äôt hide behind a GUI forever.</p>

<p class="notice-info">Looking for a place to start? I've found both [Git Immersion](http://gitimmersion.com/) and the [Pro Git](http://git-scm.com/book) book to be super helpful.</p>

    
